{"key":"processedPost-10827129","value":{"id":10827129,"first":10825994,"last":10827129,"when":1249837256,"utime":"08/09/09 08:00 PM","content":"<img src='/forums/images/moved.gif'> <b>This thread was moved from Advanced Mycology.</b><br /><br />Reason:<br />\"So I have one petri dish left of my 'golden' strain. I didnt know it was going to be the golden one until now.'<br /><br />So, how do you know it is now?&nbsp; You're supposed to label each dish with the date, species and strain.<br /><br />I wouldn't use a petri dish after a month.&nbsp; The idea of agar is to catch rapidly expanding mycelium, and to isolate it away from contaminants.&nbsp; If you're determined to use it, place a small wedge into a rye jar.&nbsp; Let it grow for a few days into the grains and then give a good shake to distribute the mycelium.<br />RR","title":"Re: Petri To Grain Question (moved)"}}